The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Thursday, August 19, 2004  Timeout
				 																DRAMA				 																																	 August 19 at Rabindra Sadan and August 20 at Academy of Fine Arts; 6.30 pm: PLT will stage its latest plat, Utpal Dutts Bibighar. Direction: Mrinal Ghosh.				 																																	 August 19 at Girish Mancha; 6.30 pm: Shohan presents Juto (dir: Anish Ghosh) and Srirangam presents Tumi Kaar (dir: Paran Bandyopadhyay).				 																																	 August 22 at Girish Mancha; 6.30 pm: Nandikar presents Buddhadev Boses Pata Jhorey Jaye (dir: Rudraprasad Sengupta) and Munshi Premchands Borda (dir: Goutam Halder).				 																																	 August 22 at Khemka Hall, Ballygunge Shiksha Sadan; 6 pm: Pancham Vaidic will stage its latest production, Rajnaitik Hatya. Direction: Saoli Mitra.				 																																	 August 22 at Mukta Angan; 6.30 pm: Shouvanik presents Washing Machine.				 																 Art				 																																	 Till August 20 at Chitrakoot Art Gallery; 2 pm - 8 pm: The Seekers  a celebration of Indias spiritual quest through paintings, photographs and sculptures of renowned artists. Curation: Ratnottama Sengupta and Prabhas Kejriwal.				 																																	 Till August 20 at Genesis Art Gallery, 8B Middleton Street; 2 pm - 7 pm: Habitat Foundation presents an exhibition of paintings by The Ash Family  Gobardhan Ash, Nirban Ash, Deborshi Ash, Jyotirmoy Ash and Chinmoy Ash.				 																																	 Till August 22 at Birla Academy of Art amp; Culture; 4 pm - 8 pm: Stroke and Chisel  an exhibition of the works of Sanatan Dinda, Subrata Gangopadhyay, Narendra Pal Singh, Ashutosh Nigam, Vijay Singh, Biman Das, Pradip Rakshit, Mohan Singh, Paresh Hazra, Noni Borpujari, Anant Nikam, S. Pranam Singh and Samit Dey.				 																																	 Till August 31 (except Sunday) at Gallery Kanishkas, 2/1 Hindustan Road; 11 am - 7.30 pm: Chitrakarer Chitrakala  an exhibition of patachitras (Midnapore pats, Kalighat pats and tribal Santhal pats of traditional folk painter Anwar Chitrakar of Pingla).				 																																	 Till September 5 at Idiyas Gallery, 15 Dover Road; 10.30 am - 7.30 pm: Paintings and sculptures by a group of renowned artists.				 																PHOTOGRAPHS				 																																	 Till August 19 at Gorky Sadan; 4 pm - 7 pm: To celebrate the return of the Olympic Games to Greece, the cultural department of the Russian Federation Consulate General in Calcutta presents Glimpses of Greece  an exhibition of photographs by Mala Mukerjee.Performing Arts				 																																	 August 19 at Ramakrishna Mission Institute of Culture, Vivekananda Hall; 6 pm: A jugalbandi featuring Biswajit Roy Chowdhury (violin) and Sanatan Goswami (harmonium), with Ananda Gopal Bandyopadhyay and Pran Gopal Bandyopadhyay on the tabla.				 																																	 August 19 at Gyan Manch; 6 pm: Komal Gandhar presents an evening of classical music featuring Esha Bandyopadhyay (vocal) and Partha Bose (sitar).				 																																	 Till August 20 at Kala Kunj; 5.30 pm: Ustad Bahadur Khan Music Circle presents its 16th annual classical music conference featuring (today) Malabika Pathak (bhajan), Krishnendu Karmakar (vocal); Bappaditya Roy (tabla lahara), Sudip Chatterjee (violin), Manikuntala Sen (vocal) and Avijit Dutta (sitar). Tomorrow: Mallika Chatterjee (bhajan), Romi Dasgupta and Rikhia Basu (Odissi amp; Manipuri), Sohini Banerjee (Kathak), Ustad Karim Sahabuddin (vocal) and Bidyut Khan (sarod)				 																																	 August 21 at Science City main auditorium; 6.30 pm: Ananda Shankar Centre for Performing Arts presents its Annual Demonstration Show. Music: Ananda Shankar. Choreography: Tanusree Shankar and faculty members.				 																																	 August 21 at Rabindra Sadan; 6.30 pm: Visva Bharati Music Board will observe Rabindra Smaran 1411 with Tagore songs by Supratik Das and Swastika Mukhopadhyay, and dance-drama Mayar Khela by Visva Bharati Sangeet Bhavan.				 																TALK				 																																	 August 19 at Ramakrishna Mission Institute of Culture, Shivananda Hall; 5 pm: Sitanath Goswami will speak in Bengali on Panchadashi.				 																																	 August 19 at Seagull Arts and Media Resource Centre (/3); 6 pm: The Seagull Foundation for the Arts presents a talk by Janaki Nair on Tipu Sultan, History Painting and the Battle for Perspective.				 																																	 August 19 at Ramakrishna Vedanta Math; 7 pm: Swami Samshuddhananda will discuss in Bengali Mandukya-Karika.				 																																	 August 19 at Ramakrishna Math, Baranagore; 7.15 pm: Discourse on Kathoupanisad by Swami Atmapriyanandaji.				 																WORKSHOP				 																																	 August 20 amp; 21 from 5 pm to 8 pm; August 22 from 4 pm to 7 pm; at Lake School for Girls: In celebration of its 30 years and the 86th birth anniversary of Guru Bipin Singh, Manipuri Nartanalaya hosts workshops on specific aspects of Lai Haraoba (Maibi Jagoi, Anoirol and Leima Jagoi), to be conducted by Kalavati Devi and Devjani Chaliha, on August 20 amp; 21; and on Aharya Abhinaya (to be conducted by Kalavati Devi) on August 22. Details at 2464-1922; 98300-29586.				 																FESTIVAL				 																																	 August 19 at Sri Ganesh Murugan Temples, Lake Gardens; 6 pm: As Guru peyarchi enters Kanya Rasi today, Sanmarga Trust presents Homam, followed by Abhisekam to Dakshinamoorthy and Lord Guru, and Archana and Prasada Viniyogam.				 																FILM SHOW				 																																	 August 19 at Nandan II; 2 pm: The screening of Suman Kumar Pauls two short films, Aamake Choto Bhebona  Little Magazine and Schooler Bagta Baddo Bhari, as part of the ongoing 1st Calcutta Short Film Festival (August 17 - 20) organised by Chitrabani.				 																IN MEMORIAM				 																																	 August 22 at Academy of Fine Arts; 6.45 pm: Gandhar remembers the late Sombhu Mitra on his 90th birthday with reading from his writings, songs from his play-productions and poems he liked.
